cracker
Homonym Number:
Word Class:noun
Sense Number:
Definition:a short piece of twisted flax etc at end of stockwhip to make it sting and crack (=? US popper)
Origin:[none]
Register:
Register 2:
Domain:[none]
Region:[none]
See:stockwhip
Pronunciation:
Notes:
Citations
Date: 0/0/1974
Source: Open Country Muster
Author: HENDERSON
Vol / Page: 178
Edition:
Quote: The boss had cut a blade of flax, and, having stripped it into whiitau, was making a cracker for his stockwhip.
Notes:

Date: 19/9/1856
Source: Diary
Author: W.H.S. ROBERTS
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote: The [bullock] whip was rawhide plaited sinnet, about six feet long, thick at the upper end, where it was fastened to a handle as long as itself, but tapering nearly to a point, to which was attached a narrow strip of rawhide, called `the fall,' finishing off with a twisted `cracker' made of `weetau' or dressed flax in [43] place of whipcord, and was a powerful flagellator in the hands of an experienced `bullock puncher.'
Notes: 1856 Sep 19 W.H.S. Roberts Diary in 1947 Beattie Early Runholding 42-43

Date: 9/12/1862
